## Summary

Allow Attribute-based customization of the "Go To Definition" (Ctrl+Click) feature in source code, so that a certain type or member can "redirect" Ctrl+Click navigation to a different type or member.

## Background and Motivation

We're currently using source-generated code extensively throughout our codebase as "glue code" to instantiate certain classes and invoke methods on these instances.

This approach works very well for us but disrupts Ctrl+Click navigation, because the source-generated code gets "in the way" and you need to do additional navigation steps to reach the actual target class.

We would like to have a way to override the behavior of Ctrl+Click and "redirect" the navigation to a different place, in a customizable user-defined way.

More specifically, we're using it for ViewModel-driven routing and popup dialogs in our Avalonia application.

So, if ViewModel `Foo` needs to route to ViewModel `Bar`, we do the following:

![image](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/assets/98904713/3c92b27a-b4e0-4abe-8a0f-2dfa4bd499f5)

- `Foo` invokes a source-generated routing method called `Bar()` that has the same parameters as the user-defined constructor of the `Bar` class.
- This method invokes a source-generated constructor of the `Bar` class that has the same parameters as the user-defined constructor, plus an additional context object.
- This constructor is based on the user-defined constructor.

We would like to be able to Ctrl+Click from the code in `Foo` directly to the user-defined constructor of `Bar` without the intermediate steps 2 and 3.

A simplified example of this:

```csharp
// User-defined class Foo
class Foo: ViewModelBase
{
    void GoToBar()
    {
        // RouteTo() returns a source-generated type that contains a method for each existing viewmodel, including a Bar() method. 
        // This method has the same parameters as the constructor of the Bar class.
        RouteTo().Bar(5); 
    }

    protected Route RouteTo() { /* ... */ }
}

// User-defined class Bar
partial class Bar: ViewModelBase
{
    // Constructor parameters are "copied" from the user-defined constructor to the source-generated RouteTo().Bar() method
    private Bar(int someValue)
    {
        // ...
    }
}
```

From this user-defined code, our source generator generates the following:

```csharp
// Auto-generated
partial class Route
{
    ContextObject context;

    // Source-generated navigation method
    // Has the same parameters as the user-defined constructor of the Bar class
    public void Bar(int someValue)
    {
         // invokes the source-generated constructor of the Bar class
         var target = new Bar(context, someValue);
         GoTo(target);
    }
}

// Auto-generated
partial class Bar
{
    // This source-generated constructor "copies" all parameters from the user-defined one, adding an additional ContextObject
    public Bar(ContextObject context, int someValue): this(someValue)
    {
        // ...
    }
}
```

As you can see, in this scenario Ctrl+click navigation from Foo to Bar requires 3 steps:
 - Ctrl+Click on `Bar` method in `RouteTo().Bar(5)` will navigate to source generated `Route.Bar(int someValue)`
 - Ctrl+Click on `Bar` type in `new Bar(context, someValue)` will navigate to source generated public constructor in class `Bar`
 - Ctrl+Click on `this` in `: this(someValue)` will finally navigate to the relevant, user-defined constructor of `Bar`.

## Proposed Feature

Create a `[GoToDefinition]` attribute that will allow to annotate the source generated code, indicating that Ctrl+Click (or Go to Definition) navigation should be redirected to a specific type and member in user-defined code and bypass anything in between.

The above generated code could be annotated like so:

```csharp
// Auto-generated
partial class Route
{
    ContextObject context;

    // Source-generated routing method
    // Attribute Indicates that Ctrl+Click of this method should really go to type Bar, constructor with arg "someValue"
    [GoToDefinition<Bar>(MemberName = "ctor", Args = new[] {"someValue"})] 
    public void Bar(int someValue)
    {
         var target = new Bar(context, someValue);
         GoTo(target);
    }
}
```

So that the `[GoToDefinition]` attribute indicates which type and member to go to when Ctrl+Clicking or selecting "Go To Definition" of the annotated method.

## Alternative Designs

None that I can think of right now.

Encountered the following issue when trying to debug an incremental source generator false positive:

## Minimal reproduction

```C#
[Fact]
public void ReturnsEqualValuesForEqualArguments()
{
    var descriptor = new DiagnosticDescriptor(
        id: "0001",
        title: "title",
        messageFormat: "Prameterized format {0}.",
        category: "category",
        defaultSeverity: DiagnosticSeverity.Warning,
        isEnabledByDefault: true);

    string arg1 = new string('a', 5);
    string arg2 = new string('a', 5);
    Assert.Equal(arg1, arg2);
    Assert.NotSame(arg1, arg2);

    Diagnostic diag1 = Diagnostic.Create(descriptor, location: null, arg1);
    Diagnostic diag2 = Diagnostic.Create(descriptor, location: null, arg2);

    Assert.Equal(diag1, diag2); // Assertion failing
}
```

The issue appears to be caused by the following line:

https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/blob/687921ffae8ad91a5464473cb1759fd463c345f2/src/Compilers/Core/Portable/Diagnostic/Diagnostic_SimpleDiagnostic.cs#L165

**Version Used**: VS 17.6

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Create a source generator, that loads an assembly with another source generator and delegates to it:

```c#
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis;
using System;
using System.Linq;
using System.Reflection;

namespace SourceGenerator
{
    [Generator(LanguageNames.CSharp)]
    public class Generator : IIncrementalGenerator
    {
        public void Initialize(IncrementalGeneratorInitializationContext context)
        {
            AppDomain.CurrentDomain.AssemblyResolve += (s, e) =>
                AppDomain.CurrentDomain.GetAssemblies()
                    .Single(x => AssemblyName.ReferenceMatchesDefinition(new AssemblyName(e.Name), x.GetName()));

            var implAssembly = Assembly.LoadFile(@"path\to\SourceGeneratorImpl.dll");

            var implType = implAssembly.GetType("SourceGenerator.GeneratorImpl");

            var impl = (IIncrementalGenerator)Activator.CreateInstance(implType);

            impl.Initialize(context);
        }
    }
}
```

The other source generator only has to use anything involving `ImmutableArray<T>`, e.g. call `Collect` on an `IncrementalValuesProvider<T>`:

```c#
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis;
using System.Collections.Immutable;
using System.Linq;

namespace SourceGenerator
{
    [Generator(LanguageNames.CSharp)]
    public class GeneratorImpl : IIncrementalGenerator
    {
        public void Initialize(IncrementalGeneratorInitializationContext context)
        {
            context.AdditionalTextsProvider.Select((text, _) => text).Collect();
        }

        public ImmutableArray<int> SomeImmutableArrayProperty { get; set; }
    }
}
```

Then reference this source generator as a NuGet package from another project and open it in Visual Studio 17.6.

**Expected Behavior**:

The source generator works (in this case, does nothing useful).

**Actual Behavior**:

The following exception is thrown when the `ServiceHub.RoslynCodeAnalysisService` process tries to run the source generator:

```
System.MissingMethodException: Method not found: 'Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.IncrementalValueProvider`1<System.Collections.Immutable.ImmutableArray`1<!!0>> Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.IncrementalValueProviderExtensions.Collect(Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.IncrementalValuesProvider`1<!!0>)'.
   at SourceGenerator.GeneratorImpl.Initialize(IncrementalGeneratorInitializationContext context)
   at SourceGenerator.Generator.Initialize(IncrementalGeneratorInitializationContext context)
   at Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.GeneratorDriver.RunGeneratorsCore(Compilation compilation, DiagnosticBag diagnosticsBag, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
```

This seems to happen, because that process has two copies of System.Collections.Immutable loaded and Microsoft.CodeAnalysis uses one, while the loaded source generator uses the other:

![](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/assets/287848/892a1847-ca08-4b0c-83cb-db61d1de7cad)

This is not a problem in the devenv process, because that only has one copy of the Microsoft.CodeAnalysis assembly loaded.

Note that this only started happening with VS 17.6.

**Version Used**: Version 17.7.0 Preview 2.0 [33721.22.main]

## `Program.cs`

```c#
using (var foo = new MyDisposable()) // not suggested here
{
}

class C
{
    void M()
    {
        using (var foo = new MyDisposable()) // suggested here
        {
        }
    }
}
```

I can't see a reason not to suggest it in the top-level context as well.

I'm working on a solution that has a lot of sample code, and therefore a lot of top-level statements. I want to fix up these samples to use modern patterns, and this will need to be done manually.
